segments.text: James R. Bradley, Director of the Texas Engineering Extension Service.
Today's date is August 6, 1981.
Mr. Bradley, could we begin by your telling us something about your early years in Galveston?
Well, I was born in Galveston in 1923 and was raised about two blocks from the beach and lived in Galveston until I was approximately
11 or 12 years old.
And when the Depression got my father's business and he had to go bankrupt, he had a small farm up in the country in Galveston County, in the little town of Altaloma.
And we moved up there about in 1932.
And I spent the rest of my high school days in the little town of Altaloma.
And then in 1940, I started .
Is that A-L-T-A-L-O-M-A?
Right.
A-L-T-A-L-O-M-A.
That's in Galveston County, too.
Okay, elaborate more on how your family was affected by the Depression, please.
Well, my father was a concrete contractor, and he had built all the warehouses on Broadway and Galveston, the Kempner warehouses.
And when the Depression hit him in 1929, he continued to stay in business until he went through all of his resources.
And when he left in 1932,
The only thing that he had was a home in this little town with about 15 acres of land, and that was his total financial resources.
I never felt the Depression myself because my father always provided for us.
And I was at such an early age, I didn't, and

first generation, my family's first generation in this country, my mother was born in Glasgow, Scotland, my father was born in Canada, and of course people like that don't tell their children problems, and I didn't even know there was a depression, I didn't even know there was a problem until after life, after later on in life, and so I wasn't really affected by it, that I could, I can look back now and see the hardships that they went through, but I didn't see it at the time.
How far was it that, was it when you moved from the big chair?
Yeah, we moved about, we lived on the west end of Galveston and we moved up to the Galveston counties about 15, 18 miles.
Okay, when did you finish high school?
I finished high school in 1940 and I started A&M in September 1940.
Do you remember the famous visit that President Roosevelt made to Galveston in 1937?
I remember it very vividly and had the opportunity to shake the President's hand when he was going down Broadway.
And his car waved to him.
Tell us more about that.
Well, back those days, we didn't have a whole lot of entertaining activity.
But whenever the president or the governor would come to your town or come close to your town, it was a family outing.
And probably more so in my family than most families, because my parents were both extremely proud to be American citizens.
They had worked extremely hard, and the United States had been extremely good to my daddy.

and whenever we had these kind of occasions my daddy did everything in the world he could to get us exposed to opportunity to see him or shake their hand or if they were going to make a speech he made sure we was there to listen to it and this was not only the president this was the governor or this was any high official the day that the president come to galliviston we were down there bright and early my mother packed a lunch and we sat in a very good position was in a very

good position when the president come by and basically because my father knew several people and we did have good good seats and I did actually touch President Roosevelt's hand when he come by in the car.
Greatest thrill I guess I ever had in my life except riding with W.O.
Daniels.
At that time, I believe it was the then Congressman-elect Lyndon Johnson participated in that meeting.
Did you see him also?
Yes, I did.
Was that the first time you had seen him?
That was the first time I'd ever seen Lyndon Johnson.
But not the last, I presume.
No, it was not the last.
No, I saw him many times.
I was with him many times.
Okay, in 1940, you came to A&M in what field?
I came to A&M in 1940, and I was in what they called Agriculture Administration, which at that time we did not have a business school.
And in the agriculture administration area, I was majoring in, you could go either accounting or you could go marketing and finance.
And I selected to go marketing and finance rather.
And you got a degree?
I got, well, my class, I was in the class of 44, and they called our class into the service one semester before we finished.
And I went into the service in March.
March 25, 1943, and we lacked one semester from graduating.

A&M went on a year-round basis in 42, so even though we hadn't been here but seven semesters, because we got that full semester in summertime, they took us out in 43, and the university let us take examinations and give us credit for that semester.
I lacked 12 hours from graduating along with just about everybody in my class.
There were some 1,100 of us.
And they took us off to Fort Sam Houston, and there we went on to Officer's Candidate School.
Those that had contracts went to Officer's Candidate School, and I went to Fort Hood.
This was the tank destroyer.
We had a former student, a gentleman, A.D. Bruce, who was father of the tank destroyers.
It was a new component in the Army.
And John Bruce come to A&M, and he recruited 35 of us,
to attend Tank Destroyers OCS, and that's where we went after we was fully inducted into the Army.
And from the Tank Destroyers School, after graduation, I stayed in Tank Destroyers as Officer of Kansas School, taught for six months, taught .30 caliber machine gun.
And then I joined the Line Outfit 692nd Tank Destroyer Battalion, and they were in the process of
getting ready to go overseas.
So shortly after I joined them, 45 days after I joined them, we went to Fort Mary, Maryland.
And from Fort Mary, Maryland we went to New York and shipped out for Europe.
And we got over there in, oh it was about in October of 1944.
After the D-Day landing, you landed, where did you go, France?
Yes, we went to France and
From France, we went on into southern Germany.
We went into Le Havre, and then went on down into southern Germany, and into Stuttgart, across the Siegfried Line.
Your group was serving under General Eisenhower?
Well, yes.
He was commander of all the troops in Europe.
As a tank destroyer battalion, you had one platoon of tank destroyers assigned to an infantry battalion.
So my battalion commander was never closer than 60 to 100 miles from me.
So I was attached to, every tank destroyer platoon, I was a platoon leader, was attached to an infantry battalion.
I was attached to the 103rd Infantry Division, the 9th Battalion of the 103rd Infantry Division.
It was commanded by General Terry Allen.
Never did see the man in my life, but I mean, that was our division commander.
And we were assigned to an infantry battalion.
And I stayed with that infantry battalion right on through until about, I guess it was about June of 1945, about a month after the war.
And then they put us into occupation.
And in the meantime, my platoon, along with the
the 45th Infantry Division, which was known as the Rainbow Division.
The last combat we saw was in Munich.
And my last assignment was we were put in to relieve concentration camp Dachau.
And I stayed about 36 hours in Munich where concentration camp Dachau was located.
Could you spell that?
D-A-C-H-U-A.
That was the camp where
The police and the people were starved to death, literally just starved to death.
And there was little big boxcars of people right outside the concentration camp.
And as soon as we got that under control,
At that time, I was a company commander.
My company commander had his arm cut off, and I'd been a company commander.
And then we were detailed to go from Concentration Camp Daukau to Concentration Camp Alok, which was about 40 miles away.
And that was a typhus fever camp.
Everybody in Concentration Camp Alok, and that's A-L-L-A-C-H, had typhus fever, both men and women.
And it was basically just a wired-in encampment with little
shelter-type cover.
I don't remember the size, but it seemed to me like now it was probably 20 or 30 acres for the females and 20 or 30 acres for the males.
They were joining each other.
They were joining each other and they just had a little shelter-like type of cover.
And of course they all had type of fever.
They were all in real bad physical health.
And we stayed there about
We stayed there about five to seven days, and then we went on.
So then our battalion, our attack destroyer battalion, was brought back together for the first time since we'd been overseas as a battalion.
And we got together in Rosenheim, Germany.
And we stayed in Rosenheim for about three days, and then each one of the companies was assigned a town to go into occupation.
And I was assigned the town of Sohuben.
That's S-O-L-H-U-E-B-E-N. Sohuben, Germany.
It was a town of about 10,000 to 12,000 population.
And I stayed in occupation there from about May the 9th to 10th, somewhere along in there, to about July to August, to about July the 1st, somewhere along there.
Because on the 4th of July, we were

moving i remember fourth of july we was moving from seoul huben down to austria it's a little town of coast of austria and it was in bavaria it was a small town and we stayed there about three and a half weeks right near to the end of august and then we was shipped home we shipped to back to camp lucky strike right out of paris and we was processed to come home and we sailed
We were three days out at sea when they dropped the first atomic bomb.
When the first atomic bomb was dropped in Japan, we stayed on.
The ship was stopped until we got further orders.
We stayed, it seemed like, for about 36 hours.
Then they barred us to the Boston port.
It took us 17 days to get back.
About two or three days of that we were there.
waiting on instructions on where we should go.
Were the men surprised when the bomb was dropped?
Definitely.
Were they not aware that such a thing was even going to happen?
Oh, there's always rumors.
During World War II, every day, you know, we heard there was a

equipment coming out or they had new some type of chemical that was going to wipe out all the enemy but leave us all healthy you know it was constant this was constant but but yes we was shocked because that's what we had been hearing about really that's what all the rumors were about but we back then as far as I was concerned I was very young and didn't have a whole lot of imagination and
I couldn't have dreamed of such a thing as an atomic bomb.
I mean, it wasn't even my wildest imagination that there would be such a weapon that could destroy the human race, the human body, and the physical plants as an atomic bomb.
I mean, I couldn't even have dreamed of something in my wildest imagination.
So certainly we were extremely shocked.
Do you think that the dropping of the bomb shortened the war in the Pacific?
Pardon?
Do you think the dropping of the bomb shortened the war in the Pacific?
It stopped the war.
It stopped the war.
Do you think that the war would have continued indefinitely without the bombs?
Well, I'm not going to say indefinitely, but it would have continued much longer than it did.
The Japanese weren't whipped until we dropped that bomb.
They were slightly bruised, but they weren't whipped.
Well, most of the men that you served with, did they approve of seeing this bomb used?
I wouldn't know.
I wouldn't have the slightest idea.
I was damn well pleased with it, I'll tell you for sure.
And I would say that most of us was, because back those days,
In my company, I didn't have anybody over probably 24 or 5 years of age.
Most of my people in my company were from 18 to 21 or 2 years of age.
There was no young person who wanted to get killed by somebody they'd never seen or heard of, so we were damn glad for the water to stop.
They were our enemy.
Okay, you came back in 1945 to the Port of Boston.
Then you came back to Galveston.
No, uh, well, I didn't get discharged.
I got, they give us 45 days leave.

Uh, they called it R&R, rest and recreation, and I did come home to the little town of Alcalon today with my folks and that, and then I didn't get discharged until, uh, I got discharged on January 13, 1946, and I was on annual leave until April 2nd, and, uh,
April the 7th, because I got married April the 2nd, but I was on annual leave until April the 7th.
And then I started school, come back and got my 12 hours off starting in June.
Where is your wife from?
She's from Fort Worth.
Okay, you came back to A&M in 46 and finished up the same year.
Yes, I finished up in the summer.
I got my 12 hours off and then I stayed on for one semester of graduate work and left in January of 47.
What did you do your graduate work in?
Same area, agriculture economics.
I just went on to agriculture economics.
Okay, then what about 1947?
What did you do?
At that time, Mobile Oil Company was, the reason I left, Mobile Oil Company was starting an executive development training program, and they recruited three.
They recruited a graduate from RISE.
I was recruited from A&M, and I was recruited from the University of Oklahoma.
And so they put us on a three-year training program, and it was the first time that they'd ever had one.
It was Magnolia Petroleum Company at that time.
It was the first program I had, the first executive training program I had.
And during that three years, I was exposed to everything Magnolia Petroleum Company.
That was their refineries, their gas, their headquarters office, the whole thing.
And then after three years of that, I was made head of their liquefied petroleum gas department.
What was his name?
Dallas.
Dallas.
And I stayed there for about two years.
a little less than two years as head of the department, and then they created this industrial economics research at Texas A&M University.
And I was contacted with, I'd been interested in coming to work in this new area at that time.
It was under the Engineering and Criminal Station.
And I come down and interviewed Dr. Miller, who was the director of the Engineering and Criminal Station at that time.
What was his first name?
Arthur W. Miller.
That's M-E-L-L-O-H. And, uh,
interviewed him and it sounded interesting and I wanted to finish my graduate work.
I just lacked, as well as I remember, about 14 or 15 hours to get my master's degree and they gave me an opportunity to work full time and take a course while I was going to school.
I'd always wanted to finish my degree so I come back with an understanding that I'd stay until I got my master's degree and then I'd leave.
That was in 1951 and I never left.
I went on and got my master's degree in 1954.
This engineering extension service was established in 1948.
What was the purpose of the organization when it was established?
Well, the whole system was established in 1948.
The activities, a lot of the activities in the engineering extension service had been going on since 1919.
Vocational touch industrial teachers started in 1919.
Our fire school started in 1931.
Our supervisor training division started in 1940.
And during the war years, a lot of the programs, a lot of the training that was done in your war class was done by that, at that time, by an organization known as the Industrial Extension Service.
That was the forerunner of the Engineering Extension Service.
And after the war,
the Board of Regents, at that time it was the Board of Directors, created the Texas A&M College system.
At that time they turned the Industrial Extension Service into the Texas Engineering Extension Service along with the other parts of the system at that time.
Now the purpose of the mandate that we have from the legislature is to provide vocational technical training programs on an extension basis to the citizens of Texas.
Now what they mean by that is this is training
basically for the employed worker.
A high percentage, upwards of 85% of all of our training programs are for the employed worker.
That's to upgrade them so they'll be more productive and more qualified for promotion.
Now since 1948, there's been quite a change in the Engineering Extension Service, and it'll be quite a change in the Engineering Extension Service the next 20 or 30 years, too.
You've got to change.
We stayed a very small organization up until about 1975.
And I didn't join the Engineering Extension Service until 1973.
I stayed as head of the Industrial Economics Research Division shortly after I joined the division.
I joined in 51 and in 58 I made head of the Industrial Economics Research Division.
And I stayed head of that until I become Director of Continuing Education and Director of Engineering Extension Service.
It was a joint appointment in 1973.
Up until that time, the university had never had a director of continuing education.
But when we come in with our rudder tire and all of our continuing education facilities, Dr. Williams created the position of director of continuing education.

And at the time, the director of the engineering extension service was retiring, Mr. Bearden, so he put me as director of both the office of continuing education and director of engineering extension service.
And I stayed in that capacity until about 1978, and then I come full time with the Engineering Extension Service.
But the period from 70, in 1973 we had, when I came into the organization, we had 72 employees, and we had a $1,700,000 budget.
And we had approximately seven or eight training divisions.
The organization started to grow, and now we have in excess of 340 employees, and we're operating at about an $18 million budget.
And when it got to this point, when it got to be about $12 million, $13 million, I come in now.
I think it's important that everyone that ever hears about the Engineering Extension Service realize that we only get 8% or 9% of our money from appropriated services.
More than 90% of our operating budget comes from fees and contracts.
So this is a self-support organization.
People that use our services pay for it.
So this is quite different than when you're on an appropriated, hard-money type organization.
Also, all of our programs are oriented to the adult citizen.
Our average age of our student would be in excess of 30 years of age.
They're adult students.
They come from every type of background, every type of educational background, every type of work background that you could possibly think of.
They're sponsored by their companies in most cases.
95% of our students, their fees are paid for by the company they work for.
And this type of adult student, if they don't get the type of training that they think is going to be helpful to them, they just get up and walk out.
So the type of instructor that we have in the engineering detention service
is a unique type of individual.
First, they have to be highly qualified.
And they're highly qualified because they're talking to people that's working with them every day of the week.
They've got to be able to teach.
They've got to be a good teacher.
They've got to be able to communicate with this adult student, which is very difficult to do.
And then the third thing is they've got to always be well prepared.
They've got to have the latest training aids.
They have well-prepared lesson plans.
There's no such thing in our type of educational program as you have to take this.
We don't have a kind of program like you have to take, like you have to take English 103 to get a degree.
None of our programs they have to take to get anything.
They ain't taking them, so they'll upgrade themselves.
And they're expensive.
So it's just a real...
real challenge to work with this type of student.
How expensive is it to take these courses?
We vary.
We have all variations of expenses.
We'll go from probably a high of $575 for a 36-hour course.
It all has its materials to maybe probably we'll charge as low as $40 for a
20-hour course in water and wastewater.
So it'll go anywhere from $40 to $575 for anywhere from a 20- to a 36-hour course.
Most of these expenses are paid by the employer?
Yes.
The major portion, we have individuals take them that's not employed, but by far the largest, well, way up in the 90% would come from their employer.
About how many instructors do we have?
We have approximately 260, 270 instructors and we have about 70 or 80 support personnel.
Are most of these instructors employed by trade schools throughout the state?
No, they're all employed by the Engineering Intentional Service.
We have a full-time staff.
That's full-time staff.
Where are these courses taught?
All over the state of Texas.
We teach in all
253 of the 254 counties.
In other words, these people are full-time employees of the Extension Service?
That is correct.
Full-time staff.
I see.
Where are some of the...
I know you have a branch in San Antonio.
Where else do you have branches?
We have four centers.
We have four regional centers.
We started in 76 creating centers.
We have one center in San Antonio.
We have about eight staff members assigned down there.
We have a center in Arlington.
We have about 20 staff members assigned in Arlington.
We have about...
We have eight or ten staff members out from West Texas and Florida in our regional center, what we call our West Texas Regional Strengthening Center.
And we're right now just getting the fourth regional center off the ground, which we'll be in the process of fixing.
We have two people.
In addition to our centers, we have offices.
We have an office in Houston with about 18 staff members.
We have an office in Huntsville with about eight staff members.
We have an office in Houston with about 18, Huntsville with about 8, 8 of 10.
We have an office in Wesley Cole that's got two staff members.
We've got an office in Lubbock with two staff members.
And then in Abilene, we've got about five staff members in Abilene.
Now, the difference between a center and an office is an office has not been
approved by, it hadn't been presented to the legislature for approval.
The center has legislative approval.
Offices, you don't have to have legislative approval.
However, when an office becomes big enough, they will go in for a center.
Okay, how many instructing personnel do you have here on campus?
Well, we've got about, the instructional personnel, probably 120.
These are full-time?
All full-time.
Everybody in the engineering service is full-time.
We do not use part-time.
Could you give us some examples of some of the types of courses that are offered?
We offer 575 different courses.
Just say give me half a dozen or so.
Well, all types of supervisor training.
We do all levels of supervisor training from the foreman right on up to top management.
We do all types of telephone training from the installation, teaching installation of the telephone to the management of a complete telephone company.
operation management.
We do the same thing for our power companies and our electric power companies.
We do everything from installation right on up to the generating plant.
We go all through the electric power utilities.
We do all types of electronic training, many computers, all types of electronic training programs.
Marine electronics is a very popular field for us.
Of course, everybody knows about our fire program.
National and international are known for our fire program.
We have probably the only hands-on training, all has its material training program in the world, and we go all over the world to put on our courses, by the way.
We go all over Europe, Spain, and several other places to put on our oil spill school.
We're very heavily involved in our vocational and industrial teachers.
We train about 80% of all the vocational and industrial teachers in the state of Texas teaching the teacher how to teach.
It's a six hours, three hour course.
They get academic credit for it.
It's a total of 18 hours.
And this is just teaching the teacher how to teach.
Lesson plans, use of visual aids, all types of construction equipment.
We have just about every type of piece of equipment that you can get, heavy equipment.
some 560 more.
I can give you a catalog if you'd like.
Yeah, I saw a catalog out in the lobby.
Tell us a little more about the fire school.
Well, fire school is one of the oldest programs we got.
It was legislated, it become under the Texas A&M University in 1931 by the act of the legislature and we got our first appropriation in 1931.
The fire school is
started out by just training municipal firemen.
And this was the only fire field that they could get in live training.
And we believe in teaching people fire training about burning fire.
You don't believe by showing them movies.
We believe they've got to get out there and feel the heat of the fire, and get the smoke in their eyes, and at least realize what the danger of it is.
We're for fire prevention.
The fire program stayed reasonably small up until about 1973 and 71, 72, 73 we started industrial fire school, started industrial training.
Right now about probably 80% of our training in the fire program is for the industrial sector.
This is for your refinery, chemical companies, all your ship companies.
We do an awful lot of training for the marine shipping industry.
We do a lot of training for ports and things of this nature, offshore drilling and these kind of things.
That program right now is about at a $4 million level.
Their budget this year will be about $4 million.
And about $3,700,000 of that comes from fees and contracts and basically from the industrial sector.
The only programs that we do for municipalities is basically for the volunteer firemen.
And we don't charge anything for that.
We've got 12 extension instructors that don't do anything but go from one volunteer fire department to another throughout the state of Texas.
Because these are the people, these people don't get anything for that service.
That public service they provide to citizens of their city, they get nothing for it.
So we don't charge them anything for their training.
However, if they didn't have volunteer fire departments, the insurance key rate would go completely out of existence.
Unbelievable.
Since they provide their time free, the legislature gives me an appropriation, and we provide the training to the volunteer fire department.
So you have them come here and then you also go to them.
Right, we do it both ways.
We have them come here once a year, basically.
Now the local volunteer fire department sometimes come out here on the weekend and use our field, but basically we go to their department.
And one week a year we have an annual municipal fire school here, and we have somewhere from 2,500 to 3,000 students participating.
When is that held each year?
It's held the second week in July.
What about a little more on vocational agricultural training?
We do no vocational agricultural training.
That's done by the Agriculture Education Department.
We don't get into agriculture at all.
What about welding?
We don't get into welding.
The only thing that we do, that's Dunbag education, the only welding we do in San Antonio, in our San Antonio training division, we have one course in welding over there.
That's our skill center, and that's a separate part of the engineering attention service.
It's the only part that we have.
We don't do it anyplace else.
We have what we call the San Antonio training division.
It has some six or seven skills.
This is skill training rather than vocational technical training.
This is skill training.
Welding is taught over there on a very limited basis, and it's a nine-month program.
And the student has to be a CEDA student, that's a Comprehensive Employment Training Act student.
The government funds the program totally, pays the student $3, whatever the minimum wage is, while they're attending class.
And they normally go for about nine months.
Now, we teach them everything.
There's more to teaching welding than just welding.
Some of these people that we have, and lots of them, first you've got to teach them
how to read instructions.
They'll spend a lot of time in what we call job-related courses, which is how to read instructions, how to use certain tools, so forth and so on.
But the program over there is a nine-month program, and welding is one of the programs, and we have others in business technology.
We've got one in auto electronics.
We've got one in sheet metal.
We've got one in radio and television repair.
But we've got some seven skill type.
And they're all long-term paid.
And that's paid for fully by the federal government.
Do you have any figures on how many people in a given year take courses under the Extension Service auspices?
Oh, yeah.
We can tell you specifically.
Last year, and it's important you have a copy of it, last year we had a little over 50,000 students.
And...
This gives you the number of student hours.
We had 1,747,000 student hours.
We had 2,094 different classes.
This gives you the programs, classes conducted, hours in session students enrolled.
We can tell you every year, this year, we're going to be at about 55,000 students.
We'll know around September.
Do you have some people who take more than one course, or most of them just take one course?
Most of them take one course.
Occasionally, you'll find one that'll
take more than one.
You'll find some that maybe will take a telephone course and then two or three years later if it gets promoted to a supervisor, they'll come into our supervisor training program.
Basically, they're within one or two areas.
Could you elaborate a little more on the supervisor training program?
Well, the supervisor training program is just a very, what we call a short course program.
They'll range from 12 hours to 40 hours.
The longest course we have in supervisor training is 40 hours.
Most of them run in the 12 to 18 hour sections.
We have about 10 or 12 different supervisor courses we start.
We can start the man just before he becomes a foreman.
Normally, the people we work with are the companies that have identified these people that they will be foremen or they will be a supervisor.
And before they get in this position, they'll normally enroll them in our courses to get a little background on what supervisor training is.
And we'll take them.
We've taken the same person from the time he took the very basic supervisor training, the basic foreman training course right on through to the case of Alamo Steel.
I think he's vice president of the company right now, and he's been to every one of them.
But we take them on up.
Most cases don't get that far.
Most times they take one or two, and that ends it.
What are some of the companies that hire the Extension Service to conduct courses for their employees?
Some of them, Dow Chemical Company, Temple Industries, Lone Star Gas, Southwestern Bell Telephone, there's 10,000.
I could go on and on and on.
Does other states have an engineering extension service like Texas has?
No, there's not another engineering extension service in the United States like the engineering extension service.
There's several engineering extension services over the state of Texas, but they're basically related to just, they're very small, and basically they're related to just a professional engineer.
Well, then Texas is a pioneer in this concept of an extension service.
It sure is.
It sure is.
Why do you suppose that this developed in Texas and not other states?
Oh, basically Texas, I would think, I can't answer your question specifically, but my opinion is that Texas was a rural state.
Texas didn't have a great deal of industry in it until the last 10 or 15 years.
We have 67 rural electric co-ops.
We have 82 little family-owned rural telephone companies.
We have thousands of little communities.
And there was no way that these people could get any training.
The cost would be prohibitive for them to go send their employees off to training.
So I think the legislature, well I think the Board of Regents of the Texas Indian University System, you know, probably had numerous requests for these types of training programs.
We are the land grant university in the state of Texas and this is a function of a land grant university.
And to these requests and then one program got started and then
A need would rise out here, and they'd contact us.
And just like we're doing right now, the reason that we are in many things as we are now is because the people asked us to do it.
They asked us to do it, and they paid for it.
We're in, you know, every day we're practically opening up a new program area because there's a need.
And people contact us because they know we have the capability of doing it.
And one thing just leads to another.
Now the state's becoming highly reasonably good industrialized.
There's going to be more and more of it as the people come into the South.
The more people that come here, the more companies come here, the more training we're going to have to do.
And we're projecting that the next 10 or 15 years in our engineering attention service are going to be high growth years.
And it might even extend much farther than that, but we can foresee that far out.
And one thing led to another.
It was a need after the rural electric co-op's music training, how to teach a man to climb a pole.
And then when we started doing that, the Texas Department of Corrections said, well, you know, we've got inmates in here.
We've got a lot of poles in our prison system, so why don't we send our inmates over there?
Well, we do about a million and a half dollars' worth of training for the inmates over at the Texas Department of Corrections.
They bring them over here, and we go over there.
If it's a high-capitalized training program, they'll bring their people here.
If we can do it with a little bit of capital goods, then we take the program there.
Then you expect this program to continue to expand through the 80s.
What are some of the ways that you think it will?
Well, it's going to expand the electronic part of our program, the electronic training division.
It's going to have rapid expansion.
The public works training division, and this is training programs that we put on for all employees of municipalities and counties.
It's going to expand rapidly.
I'm saying that because people are going to have to produce more, and the only way they can produce more is to be better trained.
That's the only way you can increase productivity is get better trained people, better equipment, better people.
Public works is going to expand rapidly.
The industrial fire school is going to expand rapidly.
We know the oil and hazardous materials are growing at a very rapid rate, faster than we can get good people.
We're just now getting inland.
All of our training has been for our water-oriented oil and hazardous material training.
We're now getting inland, and with all your railroads,
Tank trucks, tank cars going through all these major cities, and the railroad runs right through the center of every city.
That's going to take a tremendous amount of training to keep these people trained, because there are going to be accidents.
And right now, it's void as far as training is concerned.
And we've been in this for about a year, and we can't even come close to filling the request for our training programs.
That's just for inland.
That's for towns like
Every town's got a railroad going through it.
Every town's got a highway going through it.
And every town's got one or the other and sometimes both.
How do you keep your courses upgraded to meet the changing needs?
Well, we try to keep our instructors on their feet, what I call on their feet, 40 weeks a year.
And that gives them 12 weeks a year for what we call professional development, course development, annual leave, sick leave, and so forth.
So we try to keep our instructors
out of the classroom at least 12 weeks a year to let them do this.
What about the role of research in the Extension Service?
We do no research at all.
We do program development.
I don't consider that research.
We do program development.
We use research organizations.
We use our engineering experiments.
They developed our all-school school.
Our all-school school.
The Engineering Experiment Station developed that whole program for us, and then when they got it developed, we took it over and implemented it.
We use other organizations that have developed programs, and we develop our own.
We use advisory committees an awful lot in this organization.
In other words, if a company comes to us and says they want a program developed in marine electronics, we'll use that as an example.
But we'll go to the marine industry, and we will get five or six people together and
In this case, Dr. Fife worked with that committee anywhere from a week to six months in developing it correctly to make sure it gives them what they want and what they need.
And once this is developed, then we start conducting it.
There's numerous ways you do program development.
And as I said, all of our people are, they have to be outstanding people in their areas of interest, and they have to keep current.
So in doing this, we do a lot of in-house program development.
We don't call it research.
Do most of your teaching personnel hold master's degrees?
No.
I would say it depends on the area of interest.
In my... All of them have this material.
Yes, everybody in there has to have a master's degree or above.
In my telephone program, we don't have any, I don't think, with a master's degree.
Most of them are just good craftsmen.
In our...
In our teacher training program, they're all master's degree people or above.
In our electronic program, they're all BS degree people or above.
In our public works program, they're all practically master's degree.
We have one or two bachelor's degrees.
You go to our electric landing program, we've got one person in that division with a degree, and that's the division head.
Maybe two.
We've got two in that division with degrees.
The rest of them are just good craftsmen.
And it'll vary between programs.
In our construction equipment, we have two people with master's degrees.
The rest of them have no degrees.
What about the teacher training section?
Could you elaborate on that?
Well, every one of those has to have a master's degree or above.
I mean, as far as what this section does.
Well, that section trains all the vocational technical teachers in high schools and community colleges and in companies as far as anybody that's going to teach.
that's never had a teaching certificate, haven't gone through the basic courses of teaching in college.
They're good craftsmen.
Most cases, they're not even college graduates.
Your vocational technical teachers in high schools are good craftsmen, like your carpenter, welder, and all that.
So what we do is try to take the ability that they have and then teach them how to teach so they can convey it to the students.
We do, I don't know what percent, it's a high percentage, probably 75% to 90%.

Of all the teacher training for high school teachers in the vocational and industrial teachers area, and the same thing we did for Southwestern Bell, any company that's got training programs, we normally take the people that's going to do the teaching and give them these teacher training courses.
That goes for fire departments, police departments, anybody that's got a training program.
